node.text:
The Countess of Wessex has appeared on @BBC5live today, discussing the ongoing prevalence of rape and sexual violence as weapons of war in conflict around the world, and the importance of raising awareness and supporting survivors.

The episode comes ahead of the International Day for the Elimination of Sexual Violence in Conflict, on Saturday 19th June, 2021. 

📻🔊 Follow our link in bio to listen in full to her interview with @tvnaga.

node.title: "Every life is important. Every survivor is terribly important."

The Countess of Wessex, Patron, joins a virtual meeting of Brendoncare’s Havant social club earlier this week.

The Prince of Wales and The Duchess of Cornwall @clarencehouse, along with an ensemble cast of invited actors, have recorded a special reading of the festive poem, ‘Twas the Night Before Christmas.
 
The poem was recorded in support of the Actors Benevolent Fund @abf1882, of which The Prince of Wales has been Patron for over 20 years taking over the role from Her Majesty The Queen in 2000. 
 
The charity supports actors and stage managers who are unable to work due to illness, injury or old age and those experiencing financial hardship particularly during the Coronavirus pandemic. 
 
This year has been particularly difficult for those working in the industry and in April the charity launched an Emergency Grant Fund to support those in their profession who are experiencing financial hardship owing to the pandemic.

Wishing you all a peaceful Christmas Eve 💫

Ahead of VJ Day, The Princess Royal held video calls with two veterans of the Far East campaign.‬
.
HRH spoke to Syd Pidgeon, 99, who served in Burma with the Royal Army Service Corps (RASC). The RASC became @royallogisticcorps, of which The Princess is Colonel-in-Chief.‬
.
The Princess Royal also spoke to Leslie Cook, an Australian veteran who served alongside British soldiers during the Second World War.‬
.
Leslie spoke to The Princess from the Australian War Memorial in Canberra.
.
.

Via @clarencehouse “As we honour the legacy of the Windrush generation, and the invaluable contribution of Black people in Britain, I dearly hope that we can continue to listen to each other’s stories and to learn from one another. The diversity of our society is its greatest strength and gives us so much to celebrate.” Today marks the anniversary of the arrival of HMT Empire Windrush in 1948, carrying hundreds of people from the Caribbean who had been invited to help rebuild Britain in the wake of the Second World War. 
#WindrushDay is an annual celebration of Britain’s Caribbean community and their contribution to life in the UK. In a message to mark the day, The Prince of Wales reflects on his visit to @BCAheritage when Their Royal Highnesses viewed an exhibition on the history of African and Caribbean communities in Britain and met veterans from the Western Indian Association of Service Personnel.

A message from The Princess Royal to @teamgb ahead of #Tokyo2020.

The Princess Royal has a long association with the @olympics, and is President of @TeamGB and a Member of the International Olympic Committee.

Over the years, The Princess has attended many games to cheer on #TeamGB, and was involved in London's successful bid to host the 2012 Olympic Games, as Director of the London Organising Committee.

#DidYouKnow The Princess Royal was the first member of the Royal Family to have competed in the Olympic Games when she rode The Queen's horse, Goodwill, in the equestrian three-day event at the 1976 Montreal Olympic Games.

This week, The Queen joined young leaders supported by @queens_commonwealth_trust to discuss their remarkable work. Swipe ⬅️ to hear The Queen talk about the importance of teamwork in delivering vital work in the Commonwealth community, and head to our stories for more from the call. 

🇲🇻 Safaath Ahmed Zahir from the Maldives runs an NGO encouraging women’s political participation, supported by a QCT grant.

🇬🇾 Jubilanté Cutting from Guyana  helps young people in the Caribbean build skills in digital media & animation. 

🇷🇼 Jean d’Amour Mutoni from Rwanda co-founded an enterprise that supports the country’s social entrepreneurs.

🇬🇧 Brad Gudger is a two-time cancer survivor and founder of @alike.uk, a charity that aims to combat the loneliness and social isolation many young people with cancer experience though a mobile app.

With 60% of the Commonwealth population under 30, the QCT supports young people across The Commonwealth who are driving transformational change in their communities.

🎖 Congratulations to everyone who received an honour from The Prince of Wales during today’s Investiture.

Natasha Gordon was awarded an MBE for Services to Drama - her debut play Nine Night made her the first black British female playwright to be produced in the West End

🧑‍🍳 Nigel Slater was awarded an OBE for services to Cookery and Literature. Nigel has been a cook and writer for over 30 years and is the principal writer for the Observer Food Monthly supplement.

Nigel’s auto-biography Toast has won multiple awards and been adapted for stage.

🏥 Lord Simon Stevens, Chief Executive of the NHS, was awarded a KBE for services to Health and the NHS in England. 

Lord Stevens, who has worked in the NHS for over 30 years, has played a critical leadership role through the Coronavirus Pandemic.

👮‍♀️ Dame Cressida Dick, Commissioner of the Met Police, was awarded a DBE for Public Services. 

Dame Cressida became the first female Metropolitan Police Commissioner in 2017, after 38 years of police service.

She was awarded The Queen’s Police Medal for distinguished service in 2010.

A message from Her Majesty The Queen to Mr. Gareth Southgate, OBE and @england 🏴󠁧󠁢󠁥󠁮󠁧󠁿

“55 years ago I was fortunate to present the World Cup to Bobby Moore and saw what it meant to the players, management and support staff to reach and win the final of a major international football tournament.

I want to send my congratulations and that of my family to you all on reaching the final of the European Championships, and send my good wishes for tomorrow with the hope that history will record not only your success but also the spirit, commitment and pride with which you have conducted yourselves.”

- ELIZABETH R.

This week, The Prince of Wales and The Duchess of Cornwall have been carrying out their annual Wales Week. 🏴󠁧󠁢󠁷󠁬󠁳󠁿
 
♻️ On Monday, His Royal Highness joined Iceland Foods to celebrate the company’s 50th anniversary and hear about a number of their sustainability projects, including a reverse vending machine which rewards users for recycling.
 
📚 On Tuesday, The Duchess visited a number of independent bookshops and businesses in Hay-on-Wye. Here, HRH also met writers and supporters of this year’s Hay Festival, which celebrates reading and writing.
 
🎶  On Wednesday, Their Royal Highnesses saw performances at The Royal Welsh College of Music and Drama, including one by The Prince’s Official Harpist, Alis Hughes, who is an alumna of the College.
 
⛪  On Thursday, The Prince was celebrating 100 years of the Church in Wales – visiting St David’s Cathedral, St Brynach’s Church and St Martin of Tours Church.
 
Head over to @clarencehouse for more!

The Princess Royal held an Investiture at St James’s Palace earlier today. Her Royal Highness presented honours to 35 recipients from across the UK.

 🎉 Congratulations to everyone who received an honour today!

📺 June Sarpong was awarded an OBE for Services to Broadcasting. With a successful presenting career of over 20 years, June was appointed the BBC’s first Director of Creative Diversity in 2019.

June has also been an ambassador for The Prince’s Trust for over 15 years.

🧸Trevor Elliott was awarded an MBE for services to Vulnerable Children, particularly during the Coronavirus Pandemic. 

As Residential Home Manager at Ladywell Children’s Centre, part of Lewisham Children & Family Centre, Trevor supports vulnerable families in South East London.

🎭 Giles Terera was awarded an MBE for services to Theatre. Giles is best known for his role in the London production of Hamilton, the musical.

In Hamilton Giles played the role of Aaron Burr, for which he won the 2018 Olivier Award for Best Actor in a Musical.

📺 Today The Queen visited the set of the world’s longest running soap opera: Coronation Street. Last year ‘Corrie' celebrated its 60th anniversary. 

The show, a story of the everyday lives of the inhabitants of a northern town called Weatherfield, was first screened live at 7pm on Friday 9th December 1960.

More than 10,000 episodes later the programme has seen 57 births, 146 deaths and 131 weddings.

Coronation Street transmits 6 episodes a week, filming the equivalent of almost two feature films a week. It is broadcast in 105 countries around the world. The Coronation Street Production site is 7.7 acres and the biggest single television production facility of its kind in the world. 

Her Majesty met some of the 300 staff who work on Coronation Street. The programme provides employment opportunities for a variety of freelance and contractors in the creative industries in the North West.

By sighted and visually impaired people working together, the charity aims to break the cycle of sight loss unemployment.

Today The Princess Royal travelled deep below London to see the Thames Tideway Tunnel - the city’s new sewer system.

When complete, the Tunnel will help to prevent millions of tonnes of waste from polluting the Thames.

HRH fixed in the last bolt at Chelsea Embankment 🔩

"It is with great pleasure on behalf of a grateful nation, that I award the George Cross to the National Health Services of the United Kingdom.”

The George Cross was instituted in 1940 by King George VI for “acts of the greatest heroism or of the most courage in circumstances of extreme danger”.

It is the UK's highest award for non-military courage. 

This award recognises all NHS staff, past and present.

To read Her Majesty’s personal message in full, follow our link in bio.
